--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Key Findings Summary
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Your logistic regression model analyzes the factors influencing the binary outcome y using a sample size of 32 observations. 
The overall model is highly statistically significant (\(\text{Prob} > \chi^2 = 0.0015\)). Together, the predictors explain 
approximately 37.4% of the variance in the dependent variable (\(\text{Pseudo } R^2 = 0.3740\)).

A summary of the specific results follows below:
1. GPA is a strong positive predictor: A higher GPA significantly 
increases the probability of the outcome \(y = 1\) (\(p = 0.025\)). Holding other variables constant, a one-unit increase in 
GPA yields an average marginal effect of +36.3 percentage points (\(dy/dx = 0.3626\)).

2.PSI has a significant positive impact: Receiving the top-tier instruction/exposure indicator (psi) significantly boosts the likelihood of the positive outcome (\(p = 0.025\)). 
Participation in psi increases the probability of \(y = 1\) by an average of 30.5 percentage points (\(dy/dx = 0.3052\)).

3. TUCE score is not statistically significant: The tuce variable does not have a reliable impact on the outcome variable (\(p = 0.501\) 
for coefficients; \(p = 0.493\) for marginal effects). Its effect cannot be distinguished from zero in this sample.

The model fits the data well: The Pearson goodness-of-fit test shows a \(p\)-value of 0.5043. 
Because this \(p\)-value is well above the standard 0.05 threshold, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, 
meaning the model's specified structure matches the observed data adequately